The solution is useFactory instead of UseClass, change your code like the below example :
At first, create a factory class with a decision to DI logic:
```
export function myFactory() {
  if(myRule){
       return new FirstRESTService();
    }
  return new  SecondRESTService();
}
```
Then change your component code  to :
```
@Component({
  selector: &#39;this-is-tag&#39;,
  template: htmlStr,
  providers: [{ provide: RESTToken, useFactory: myFactory}],
```
Sometimes there will be a situation, you want to add some dependencies to the factory because you need it to decide whether to return serviceA or serviceB.
To satisfy this we can use deps property like this:
```
export function myFactory(obj:MyDependencyClass) {
  if(obj.HasMyRule){
       return new FirstRESTService();
    }
  return new  SecondRESTService();
}
```
also,in your component:
```
@Component({
  selector: &#39;this-is-tag&#39;,
  template: htmlStr,
  providers: [{ provide: RESTToken, useFactory: myFactory}],
  deps: [MyDependencyClass]
```
but don&#39;t forget to include MyDependencyClass in app.module.ts.

