I am using a `HttpInterceptor` to add an authorization token to each API request.
Then i subscribe to this request using `next.handle(newRequest).subscribe(...)` and inspect the result/error returned.

When the request succeeds it will just be passed on.
But when it does not because the authorization token is invalid, the interceptor refreshes the authorization token and re-tries the request.
If that retry fails the whole process fails as i intend.

Then issue is, that multiple requests can and will be sent at nearly the same time, leading to the situation, that the earlier request finds out, that the auth token is expired and initiates the token refresh process. Then - before the refreshed token is returned by the server - the second call makes a request with the expired auth token, resulting in another refresh, making the first refreshs&#39; &quot;new&quot;ly acquired auth token invalid, etc. Both calls will succeed on the retry, but this can lead up to 100 refreshes in rapid succession.

**Questions**

 1. How to defer all requests after the first one while the first is refreshing the auth token, so that each subsequent request uses the first ones&#39; newly acquired auth token?

 2. Is viable to use a member variable holding a promise which will be created on each refresh, by the first intercepting call and for which other calls wait? Or can a second near-simultanious call slip through the promise creation? Pseudo-Code for this:


```
class Interceptor  implements HttpInterceptor
{
  private refreshPromise: Promise&lt;void&gt;;

  private authToken;

  intercept(req, next)
  {
    // ... subscribe for request with auth token added...
    observable.subscribe(
      result =&gt; // ... do something
      error =&gt; {
        //... if error because of token expiration

        if(this.refreshPromise)
          await this.refreshPromise;

        this.refreshPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) =&gt; 
        {
          refreshToken().subscribe(
            result =&gt; { 
              this.authToken = result.token;
              resolve();
              this.refreshPromise = null;
            },
            error =&gt; // all is lost
          );
        });
      }
    );
    // ... request fails
  }
}
```

I suppose this is not feasible, because when i `null the promise`, those queued and not executed already will fail or will everyone awaiting the promise be notified before the nulling?!?

**Alternative Approach**

My second idea was to have a member variable flag which indicates wether a refresh is running or not, and in case it is, the requests passed to those calls of `intercept` will be added to a list of deferred requests and be executed by the first interceptor after the refresh.

The issue with this approach is the handling of the `HttpRequests` of other calls to `intercept` by the first call to intercept. Because the chain from HttpClient to HttpBackend will be broken and i cannot return the results of the deferred requests as results for the first one.

Any suggestions or solutions?

Kind Regards

